<subSubSection id="7C386C6C041F0F18CFF8F1B9937F80F3" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" type="description">
<paragraph id="096F0ADDFDFFB7D8BB2FE9A60ED4BF76" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9532A728B0A2BD21C0DE78D9BB403098" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">
Intricately branched spiny undershrub to 60 cm, stems finely adpressed pubescent, branches spinescent and with some stem spines near branch tips formed from old peduncles. Leaves sessile, 0.5-1.2 
<normalizedToken id="121FB274516A55B5D50B6A011E692D7D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.4 cm, oblong to oblanceolate, obtuse, margin entire, base attenuate, adpressed-pubescent. Flowers axillary, usually solitary, sometimes up to 3 in a diachasial cyme; peduncles 4-8 mm, woody, spinescent, bent at apex; bracteoles 1-1.5 mm, scale-like; pedicels c. 1 mm; outer sepals 3 
<normalizedToken id="AC245B188B8343D0E0FE15EA362B41DE" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2 mm, oblong to elliptic, obtuse and mucronate, convex, pubescent with spreading hairs; inner sepals 4.5-5 
<normalizedToken id="94541C9D153615CBC0B988B00FF551D9" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm, pubescent with spreading hairs; corolla 1.3-1.6 cm long, white, midpetaline bands adpressed pilose; ovary pubescent; style pubescent, divided c. 4 mm above base, stigmas 3 mm; capsule comose; seeds smooth, glabrous. [
<bibRefCitation id="E3EE6AFC06C9A8AD5AC400A5450E42D1" author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken id="952EE1D36A3862339201B1355F777D18" originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 70; 
<bibRefCitation id="0A2FAD6610A41146F54702CB7DDB3C6B" author="Austin, DF" editor="Nasir, E" journalOrPublisher="Dept. of Botany, University of Karachi, Karachi" pageId="198" pageNumber="199" pagination="1 - 64" refId="B13" refString="Austin, DF, Ghazanfar, S, 1979. Convolvulaceae. In: Nasir, E, Ali, SI, Eds., Flora of Pakistan 126: Convolvulaceae. Dept. of Botany, University of Karachi, Karachi: 1 - 64" title="Convolvulaceae." volumeTitle="Flora of Pakistan 126: Convolvulaceae." year="1979">Austin and Ghazanfar 1979</bibRefCitation>
: 12; 
<bibRefCitation id="D9E39C520BAE4950459679D203BE9FC4" author="Nowroozi, M" journalOrPublisher="Ministry of Jihad-e-Agriculture, Iran" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1 - 110" refId="B244" refString="Nowroozi, M, 2002. Flora of Iran 40: Convolvulaceae. Ministry of Jihad-e-Agriculture, Iran: 1 - 110" title="Flora of Iran 40: Convolvulaceae" year="2002">Nowroozi 2002</bibRefCitation>
: 27 (plate), 100 (map)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7229325A76C305B05BC58B1C00E5F227" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C878CE9C355C10D9C08C3B22F4A71CC5" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="65F6F3AB6340FF3356E2AF8DB9915475" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">
Iran (
<emphasis id="403A89E7A027A322E9AE960E45F1924C" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Parris</emphasis>
75.477, 
<emphasis id="88F180BE4912B05446267A18F6D52C34" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Faroughi</emphasis>
10731, 
<emphasis id="8C13D1A14B53972283B32EF78F9B0A06" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Ruenemark et al.</emphasis>
22367, 
<emphasis id="3897B6C0FB9C2233A266F6E47A6D48DE" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Aucher-Eloy</emphasis>
1279); Afghanistan (
<emphasis id="BBDB5ECEA176C99DF94FBAF84057DBA3" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Breckle</emphasis>
1074); Pakistan: Balochistan (
<emphasis id="AC34865A3606004306547B3AA1CBDCFE" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Lamond</emphasis>
1224, 
<emphasis id="9B5726852B04F9251144192832C6D437" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Ghafoor &amp; Goodman</emphasis>
4994, 
<emphasis id="8D8AD822ED3C83D8BC52C260DFE523B9" italics="true" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Rechinger</emphasis>
28121, 29401). Most common in Balochistan.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BECFA18D3C07A8710C378C5E4C1A352B" pageId="156" pageNumber="157" type="notes">
<paragraph id="5382A4B65D919C85AA8E457388E3BC6A" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0E178A3DADE7840B254F1A5B451897C7" pageId="156" pageNumber="157">The inner sepals are noticeably longer than the outer sepals.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
